            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "The original request didn't contain the referrer header, simple as that. If it does get sent along with the request it will certainly be inside `request.headers`.\n\n> EnvironHeaders([('Referer', 'http://127.0.0.1:5000/public'), ('Content-Length', ''), ('Accept-Charset', 'ISO-8859-1,utf-8;q=0.7,_;q=0.3'), ('User-Agent', 'Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux i686) AppleWebKit/537.11 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/23.0.1271.64 Safari/537.11'), ('Connection', 'keep-alive'), ('Cookie', 'session=eyJsb2dnZWRfaW4iOnRydWV9.A3iL5A.rro3BauY-qPGAzGA0eJazxAkomU'), ('Host', '127.0.0.1:5000'), ('Cache-Control', 'max-age=0'), ('Accept', 'text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,_/*;q=0.8'), ('Accept-Language', 'en-US,en;q=0.8'), ('Content-Type', ''), ('Accept-Encoding', 'gzip,deflate,sdch')])\n\nFor hotlink protection you would probably look into production server solutions. Werkzeug is not mean for production at all.\n\nhttp://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/apache-mod_rewrite-hot-linking-images-leeching-howto/\nhttp://nginxlibrary.com/hotlink-protection/\netc.\n\nBut don't depend on the referrer header being there. Helps in most leeching cases, where regular browsers are used by clients.\n\nFeel free to shut this issue down as not being a valid issue with Flask.\n"
